name: John Duffy
tweet: @CoachTLambVB @edmunds_dr Coach, first, I hope you’re not that condescending to your students. The force applied by the runner’s foot, is towards the rear, the force of friction IS in the opposite direction (forward). It’s a tricky free body diagram that’s used to really make student think.

name: John Duffy
tweet: @CoachTLambVB @edmunds_dr In this case, think of the runner’s foot. The muscles of the leg are pushing backwards. The shoes provide a frictional force forward, allowing the runner to move. If he was on ice, with no friction, the feet would slip and the runner would have no forward motion.
